 and still don't. 9 out of 10 times I can tell you that by the way a student acts long before I meet their parents. The teenager that was brought up well as a child is rarely the teenager who gets into trouble with the school authorities and the law. Every year, in every group of 8th graders we get at least one parent who basically spoiled...let run...their child and now all of a sudden does not know what to do with this teenager who is in trouble all the time...we all want to say, &quot;well, duh..did you think he would raise himself??? stupid woman (man)&quot;. <br>
<br>
I have read a lot of this thread, and skipped a lot too...but I would have to say that spanking has its place in discipline for some children and some situations and saying you just don't believe in spanking, if you have a child with the right personality, could lead to disaster. Most children, the ones who respond to spanking, who are not spanked will only turn out to be spoiled brats. THen there are those who will be kicked out for writing death threats in their journals. We get one a year. <br>
<br>
I am lucky so far and my daughter responds well to a dissaproving look and telling her she isn't being nice. She wants more than anything to be nice. She is four. Do I think this will always work? No, not likely. Do I think this is the only way to discipline her? Not at all. If she does something that might hurt her or something more serious than saying something mean to her cousin, she deserves more discipline. The trick is to match the discipline to the action...and the discipline to your child's personality (if it doesn't bother them it isn't discipline...to realize that it is your JOB to raise these kids even when it is not convenient or fun. ESPECIALLY when it is not convenient or fun, for this is when your child is learning the most.<br>
<br>
If you do your job when your children are little, most likely it won't be your child suspended for threatening teachers or other students, it won't be your child arrested for taking a gun to school, it won't be your child dead from a gunshot wound to the head after killing students and teachers at school. <br>
<br>
<br>
Aidiene<br>
