<br>
1.  To imply that all criminals are the result of bad parenting is a tough case to make.  Maybe I am spreading it too generally, but in essence all criminals were once kids, so its not to far of a stretch.  People make choices and far be it for me to know why they do.  <br>
<br>
2.  On parenting in general, i think that the most important things are consistency and follow through.  Without it, any punishment is nothing but a threat with the possibility of becoming a reality.  I do not have any kids, but I watch my friends interact with theirs.  It is this constant struggle for power.  Kids always trying for that extra &quot;bit&quot;.  I see how they threaten the kid with &quot;X&quot; punishment only to not enforce it when the child doesn't comply.  These are the lessons that are hard to unteach.  A. they learn that Mommy/ Daddy doesn't always mean what they say (concept of lying)  B.  that breaking the rules doesn't always have consequences.  Not meaning to sounds preachy *L* Just observations from a sompletely unqualified source <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
